Introduction

This document contains the source codes and corresponding execution results for exploring the daily lifestyle impacting physical fitness among adults in Xuzhou CIty, including all detailed codes for tables, figures, and the adopted models (multiple linear regression, binary logistic regression, linear mixed model) with standard diagnostics.

Load necessary package and data

rm(list = ls())
pkg <- c('car','pROC','ltm','tidyverse','rstatix','bruceR','cowplot','lmerTest','sjPlot','sjmisc','sjlabelled','readxl','openxlsx','foreign','rms','magrittr','glmmTMB')
lapply(pkg,function(x){library(x,character.only = T)})
data <- read_excel("E:/Rticedata/adults/adultsdata.xlsx")
selected_columns <- c(1:2,6,7,8,9,12,13,16,19,22,25,28,31,34,37,40,43,46,49,52,55,58,61,64,67:87,89:97,99,101,103,105,107,113,115,117,119)
new_data <- data[, selected_columns]

Data clean

Fill missing value

cols_to_fill <- c(27:37, 42:44)
new_data[, cols_to_fill][is.na(new_data[, cols_to_fill])] <- 0

Remove all missing values

new_data_cleaned <- na.omit(new_data)

Select samples

set.seed(200)
unqualified_indices <- which(new_data_cleaned$PFS == "0")
qualified_indices <- which(new_data_cleaned$PFS == "1")
num_samples_to_extract <- length(unqualified_indices) * 2.5
random_indices <- sample(qualified_indices, num_samples_to_extract)
selected_indices <- c(unqualified_indices, random_indices)
new_dataset <- new_data_cleaned[selected_indices, ]
data <- new_dataset[sample(nrow(new_dataset)), ]

Data processing

mydata <- data %>% 
  mutate(
    PFS = factor(case_when(PFS == 0 ~ 'Unqualified',
                           PFS == 1 ~ 'Qualified'),
                levels = c('Unqualified','Qualified')),
    gender = factor(case_when(gender == 1 ~ 'Male',
                              gender == 2 ~ 'Female'),
                    levels = c('Female','Male')),
    age_group.ord = factor(case_when(age_group == 1 ~ '20-29',
                                     age_group == 2 ~ '30-39',
                                     age_group == 3 ~ '40-49',
                                     age_group == 4 ~ '50-59'),
                           levels = c('20-29','30-39','40-49','50-59'),ordered = T),
    region = factor(case_when(region == 1 ~ 'Village',
                              region == 2 ~ 'Urban Manual Workers',
                              region == 3 ~ 'Urban Non-Manual Workers'),
                             levels = c('Village','Urban Manual Workers','Urban Non-Manual Workers')),
    educational_level.ord = factor(case_when(educational_level == 1 ~ 'High School and Below',
                                             educational_level == 2 ~ 'College Degree',
                                             educational_level == 3 ~ 'Bachelor Degree and Above'),
                                   levels = c('High School and Below','College Degree','Bachelor Degree and Above'),ordered = T),
    frequency_of_exercise.ord = factor(case_when(frequency_of_exercise == 1 ~ 'No Exercise',
                                                 frequency_of_exercise == 2 ~ 'Once a Week',
                                                 frequency_of_exercise == 3 ~ 'Twice a Week',
                                                 frequency_of_exercise == 4 ~ 'Three Times a Week',
                                                 frequency_of_exercise == 5 ~ 'Four Times a Week',
                                                 frequency_of_exercise == 6 ~ 'Five Times a Week',
                                                 frequency_of_exercise == 7 ~ 'More Than Five Times a Week'),
                                       levels = c('No Exercise','Once a Week','Twice a Week','Three Times a Week','Four Times a Week','Five Times a Week','More Than Five Times a Week'),ordered = T),
    exercise_time.ord = factor(case_when(exercise_time == 1 ~ 'Less Than 30 Minutes at a Time',
                                         exercise_time == 2 ~ 'Between 30 and 60 Minutes at a Time',
                                         exercise_time == 3 ~ 'More Than 60 Minutes at a Time'),
                               levels = c('Less Than 30 Minutes at a Time','Between 30 and 60 Minutes at a Time','More Than 60 Minutes at a Time'),ordered = T),
    type_of_occupation = factor(case_when(type_of_occupation == 1 ~ 'Professional Technicians',
                                          type_of_occupation == 2 ~ 'Clerical Staff',
                                          type_of_occupation == 3 ~ 'Commercial and Service Industry Workers',
                                          type_of_occupation == 4 ~ 'Agricultural Industry Workers',
                                          type_of_occupation == 5 ~ 'Other Workers',
                                          type_of_occupation == 6 ~ 'Unemployed'),
                                levels = c('Professional Technicians','Clerical Staff',
                                           'Commercial and Service Industry Workers',
                                           'Agricultural Industry Workers',
                                           'Other Workers','Unemployed')),
    hypertension = factor(case_when(hypertension == 0 ~ 'No',
                                    hypertension == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                          levels = c('No','Yes')),
    hyperlipidemia = factor(case_when(hyperlipidemia == 0 ~ 'No',
                                      hyperlipidemia == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                            levels = c('No','Yes')),
    high_cholesterol = factor(case_when(high_cholesterol == 0 ~ 'No',
                                        high_cholesterol == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                              levels = c('No','Yes')),
    diabetes = factor(case_when(diabetes == 0 ~ 'No',
                                diabetes == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                      levels = c('No','Yes')),
    coronary_heart_disease = factor(case_when(coronary_heart_disease == 'FALSE' ~ 'No',
                                              coronary_heart_disease == 'TRUE' ~ 'Yes'),
                                    levels = c('No','Yes')),
    peptic_ulcer = factor(case_when(peptic_ulcer == 0 ~ 'No',
                                    peptic_ulcer == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                          levels = c('No','Yes')),
    osteoarticular_diseases = factor(case_when(osteoarticular_diseases == 0 ~ 'No',
                                               osteoarticular_diseases == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                                     levels = c('No','Yes')),
    cervical_spondylosis = factor(case_when(cervical_spondylosis == 0 ~ 'No',
                                            cervical_spondylosis == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                                  levels = c('No','Yes')),
    occupational_disease = factor(case_when(occupational_disease == 0 ~ 'No',
                                            occupational_disease == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                                  levels = c('No','Yes')),
    unknown = factor(case_when(unknown == 0 ~ 'No',
                               unknown == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                     levels = c('No','Yes')),
    no_disease = factor(case_when(no_disease == 0 ~ 'No',
                                  no_disease == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                        levels = c('No','Yes')),
    whether_to_exercise_or_not = factor(case_when(whether_to_exercise_or_not == 0 ~ 'No',
                                                  whether_to_exercise_or_not == 1 ~ 'Yes'),
                                        levels = c('No','Yes')),
    feelings_during_exercise.ord = factor(case_when(feelings_during_exercise == 1 ~ 'No burden',
                                                    feelings_during_exercise == 2 ~ 'A slight burden',
                                                    feelings_during_exercise == 3 ~ 'A heavy burden'),
                                          levels = c('No burden',
                                                     'A slight burden',
                                                     'A heavy burden'),ordered = T),
    exercise_projects = factor(case_when(exercise_projects == 0 ~ 'None',
                                         exercise_projects == 1 ~ 'Jogging',
                                         exercise_projects == 2 ~ 'Swimming',
                                         exercise_projects == 3 ~ 'Walking',
                                         exercise_projects == 4 ~ 'Ball',
                                         exercise_projects == 5 ~ 'Mountaineering',
                                         exercise_projects == 6 ~ 'Cycling',
                                         exercise_projects == 7 ~ 'Other'),
                   levels = c('None','Jogging','Swimming','Walking','Ball','Mountaineering',
                              'Cycling','Other')),
    exercise_reasons = factor(case_when(exercise_reasons == 0 ~ 'None',
                                        exercise_reasons == 1 ~ 'Recreation',
                                        exercise_reasons == 2 ~ 'Increase Physical Activity',
                                        exercise_reasons == 3 ~ 'Reduce Stress and Regulate Mood',
                                        exercise_reasons == 4 ~ 'Weight Loss',
                                        exercise_reasons == 5 ~ 'Bodybuilders',
                                        exercise_reasons == 6 ~ 'Prevent Disease',
                                        exercise_reasons == 7 ~ 'Other'),
                             levels = c('None','Recreation','Increase Physical Activity',
                                        'Reduce Stress and Regulate Mood','Weight Loss','Bodybuilders',
                                        'Prevent Disease','Other')),
    exercise_disorders = factor(case_when(exercise_disorders == 0 ~ 'None',
                                          exercise_disorders == 1 ~ 'Not Interested',
                                          exercise_disorders == 2 ~ 'Laziness',
                                          exercise_disorders == 3 ~ 'Not Advisable or Necessary to Participate',
                                          exercise_disorders == 4 ~ 'Lack of Time',
                                          exercise_disorders == 5 ~ 'Lack of On_Site Facilities',
                                          exercise_disorders == 6 ~ 'Lack of Guidance',
                                          exercise_disorders == 7 ~ 'Lack of Organization',
                                          exercise_disorders == 8 ~ 'Other'),
                               levels = c('None','Not Interested','Laziness',
                                          'Not Advisable or Necessary to Participate',
                                          'Lack of Time','Lack of On_Site Facilities','Lack of Guidance',
                                          'Lack of Organization', 'Other'))
  )

Define the function of showing mean and standard deviation (SD).

meansd <- function(x) {
  md = round(mean(x),digits = 2)
  sd = round(sd(x),digits = 2)
  return(paste0(md,'±',sd))
}

Generate Table 1 and Table S1

The categorical and ordinal variables were described by frequency and constituent ratio, and their differences between groups were compared by Chi-square test.

a <- mydata %>% select(where(is.factor)) %>% map(.,table)
rate.tab.nomarg <- function(x){round(proportions(x)*100,2)}
rate.tab <- function(x){round(proportions(x,margin = 2)*100,2)}
a.rate <- a %>% map(.,rate.tab.nomarg)

Implement Chi-square test and display the results.

c <- mydata %>% select(where(is.factor)) %>% 
  map(.,~chisq.test(table(.x,mydata$PFS))) %>% print
## $PFS
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  table(.x, mydata$PFS)
## X-squared = 1356.1, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
## 
## $gender
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  table(.x, mydata$PFS)
## X-squared = 0.26439, df = 1, p-value = 0.6071
## 
## 
## $region
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(.x, mydata$PFS)
## X-squared = 21.303, df = 2, p-value = 2.366e-05
## 
## 
## $type_of_occupation
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(.x, mydata$PFS)
## X-squared = 19.413, df = 5, p-value = 0.00161

## 
## $hypertension
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
##

## $hyperlipidemia
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction

Implement Levene’s test to check homoscedasticity of continuous variables among subgroups.

levene <- function(vb) {
  levene_test(vb ~ PFS,data = mydata)$p
}
leven.reslt <- mydata %>% 
  select(where(is.numeric)) %>% 
  map(levene) %>% unlist %>% round(.,digits = 4) %>% print

Generate Table S2.

Total physical test scores for adults with different characteristics.

fenzuvb <- c(quo(gender),quo(age_group.ord),quo(region),
             quo(educational_level.ord),quo(type_of_occupation),quo(whether_to_exercise_or_not),
             quo(frequency_of_exercise.ord),quo(exercise_time.ord),
             quo(feelings_during_exercise.ord),quo(exercise_projects),quo(exercise_reasons),
             quo(exercise_disorders),quo(hypertension),
             quo(hyperlipidemia),quo(high_cholesterol),
             quo(diabetes),quo(coronary_heart_disease),
             quo(peptic_ulcer),quo(osteoarticular_diseases),
             quo(cervical_spondylosis),quo(occupational_disease),
             quo(unknown),quo(no_disease))

options(digits=5)

for (i in seq_along(fenzuvb)) { 
  mydata %>% group_by(!!fenzuvb[[i]]) %>% 
    summarise(
      n = round(n(),2),
      percent = n()/dim(mydata)[1]*100,
      TPTS = meansd(TPTS)
    ) %>% print
}

Use Levene’s test to check homoscedasticity among subgroups.

levene <- function(vb) {
  levene_test(TPTS ~ vb,data = mydata)$p
}
leven.reslt <- mydata %>% 
  select(gender,age_group.ord,region,educational_level.ord,type_of_occupation,whether_to_exercise_or_not,
         frequency_of_exercise.ord,exercise_time.ord,feelings_during_exercise.ord,
         exercise_projects,exercise_reasons,exercise_disorders,hypertension,
         hyperlipidemia,high_cholesterol,diabetes,coronary_heart_disease,
         peptic_ulcer,osteoarticular_diseases,cervical_spondylosis,occupational_disease,
         unknown,no_disease) %>% 
  map(levene) %>% unlist %>% round(.,digits = 5)

Display variables that satisfy homoscedaticity.

(leven.reslt.great <- leven.reslt[leven.reslt > 0.05]) 
##                       region    frequency_of_exercise.ord

Use t test or ANOVA to compare differences among subgroups. Post-hoc test is performed by Tukey’s method when homoscedasticity is satisfied, otherwise Games-Howell’s test.

ttest <- function(vb) {
  anova_summary(aov(mydata$TPTS ~ vb))$p # t test or anova
}
mydata %>% select(all_of(names(leven.reslt.great))) %>% 
  map(ttest) %>% unlist %>% round(.,digits = 5) %>% print

welchtest <- function(vb) {
  welch_anova_test(mydata$TPTS ~ vb, data = mydata)$p
}

Weighted multiple linear regression (Weighted MLR)

The standard regression diagnostics were processed with the following steps:

  1. Detect the multicollinearity between explanatory variables through variance inflation factor (VIF).

  2. Detect the homoscedasticity of residuals.

  3. Check the independence of residuals with Durbin-Waston’s test.

  4. Detect the normality of residuals.

  5. Check the linear relationship between the dependent and explanatory variables.

  6. Check the extreme values.

reg.formula <- as.formula(
  TPTS ~ gender + age + age_group + region + educational_level + type_of_occupation + minutes_of_taking_vehicles_per_week 
  + minutes_of_driving_per_week + minutes_of_riding_motorcycle_per_week + minutes_of_riding_bicycle_per_week + minutes_by_foot_per_week 
  + other_travel_minutes_per_week+ minutes_of_sedentary_behavior_per_week + minutes_with_standing_per_week + minutes_with_walking_per_week 
  + minutes_to_manual_labor_per_week + other_working_minutes_per_week + minutes_to_watch_TV_per_week + minutes_to_play_chess_per_week 
  + minutes_to_read_books_per_week + minutes_to_stroll_per_week + minutes_of_light_housework_per_week + minutes_of_heavy_housework_per_week 
  + other_active_minutes_per_week + hypertension + hyperlipidemia + high_cholesterol + diabetes + coronary_heart_disease + peptic_ulcer 
  + osteoarticular_diseases + cervical_spondylosis + occupational_disease + unknown + no_disease + whether_to_exercise_or_not + frequency_of_exercise 
  + exercise_time + feelings_during_exercise + exercise_projects + exercise_reasons + exercise_disorders + chest_circumference + waist_circumference + hip_circumference + upper_arm_skin_fold_thickness 
  + scapular_skin_fold_thickness + abdomen_skin_fold_thickness + resting_heart_rate + systolic_blood_pressure + diastolic_blood_pressure 
)
tice <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata)

There exists multicollinearity among age and age group. Thus, remove age in the regression formula.

reg.formula <- update(reg.formula, . ~ . -age)
mydata.out <- mydata
tice <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata.out)

Detect the homoscedasticity of residuals.

performance::check_heteroscedasticity(tice)
## Warning: Heteroscedasticity (non-constant error variance) detected (p < .001).

The homoscedasticity of residuals dose not satisfy, and the independency is satisfied. Thus, weight MLR will be adopted to solve heteroscedasticity. The weights were inversely proportional to the variance of the dependent variable. Regress the absolute values of the residuals against the fitted values, and the resulting fitted values squared of this new regression will be the desired estimate of this variance.

wt <- 1 / lm(abs(tice$residuals) ~ tice$fitted.values)$fitted.values^2

Perform weighted least squares regression.

wls.model <- lm(formula = reg.formula, data = mydata.out, weights=wt)

Check the independence of residuals with Durbin-Waston’s test.

performance::check_autocorrelation(wls.model)
## OK: Residuals appear to be independent and not autocorrelated (p = 0.528).

Detect the normality of residuals

performance::check_normality(wls.model)
## OK: residuals appear as normally distributed (p = 0.105).

Plot S1

Visual inspection did not reveal any significant linear or normal deviations or extreme values.

performance::check_model(wls.model,check=c('linearity','normality','homogeneity','outliers'))

Table S3

Comparison of models before and after weighting。

performance::compare_performance(tice,wls.model)

  age_group.ord.MLR = factor(cut(age_group,breaks = 4,labels=c(1,2,3,4)),ordered = T),

Binary logistic regression (BLR)

The diagnostics were processed with the following steps:

  1. Detect the multicollinearity between explanatory variables through variance inflation factor (VIF).

  2. Check the independence of residuals with Durbin-Waston’s test.

  3. Check the linear relationship between the dependent and explanatory variables.

  4. Check the extreme values.

reg.formula.logi <- update(reg.formula,PFS ~ .)
mydata.logi.out <- mydata
tice.logi <- glm(
  formula = reg.formula.logi,
  family  = binomial(link = "logit"),
  data    = mydata.logi.out
)

Plot Figure S2 of linearity.

Check the linear relationship between the dependent and explanatory variables.

mydata.logi.out <- mydata.logi.out %>% mutate(
  prob = predict(tice.logi,type = 'response'),
  logitP = log(prob/(1-prob))
)
reg.formula.logi.linear <- update(reg.formula, logitP ~ .)
logi.linear <- lm(formula = reg.formula.logi.linear, data = mydata.logi.out)
performance::check_model(logi.linear,check=c('linearity'))

Plot S6

inear and quadratic trend between age group and TPTS in BLR.

ggplot(mydata.logi.out) +
  aes(x = age_group.ord.BLR, y = logitP) +
  geom_point(shape = 1) +
  geom_smooth(aes(x = unclass(age_group.ord.BLR), color = "1"), 
              formula = y ~ x, 
              method = lm, se = FALSE) +
  geom_smooth(aes(x = unclass(age_group.ord.BLR), color = "2"), 
              formula = y ~ x + poly(x, 2), 
              method = lm, se = FALSE) +
  scale_color_discrete("Trend", labels = c("linear", "quadratic")) +
  labs(x = 'Age group',y = 'logit Physical Fitness')

ROC of BLR.

predict_<-predict.glm(tice.logi,type='response',newdata = mydata.logi.out)
modelroc <- roc(mydata.logi.out$PFS,predict_) 
## Setting levels: control = Unqualified, case = Qualified
## Setting direction: controls < cases
plot(modelroc
     ,print.auc=TRUE
     ,auc.polygon=TRUE
     ,legacy.axes=TRUE
     ,grid=c(0.1, 0.2)     ,grid.col=c("grey", "grey")
     ,max.auc.polygon=TRUE
     ,auc.polygon.col="skyblue"
     ,print.thres=TRUE
)

Weighted linear mixed model (Weighted LMM)

The regression diagnostics were processed with the following steps:

  1. Check outliners.

  2. Detect multicollinearity.

  3. Check the independence of residuals with Durbin-Waston’s test.

  4. Detect the homoscedasticity of residuals.

  5. Significance of random effects was checked by likelihood ratio test.

  6. Check the linear relationship between the dependent and explanatory variables.

mixed.reg.formula <- as.formula(
  TPTS ~ gender  + type_of_occupation + minutes_of_taking_vehicles_per_week 
  + minutes_of_driving_per_week + minutes_of_riding_motorcycle_per_week + minutes_of_riding_bicycle_per_week + minutes_by_foot_per_week 
  + other_travel_minutes_per_week+ minutes_of_sedentary_behavior_per_week + minutes_with_standing_per_week + minutes_with_walking_per_week 
  + minutes_to_manual_labor_per_week + other_working_minutes_per_week + minutes_to_watch_TV_per_week + minutes_to_play_chess_per_week 
  + minutes_to_read_books_per_week + minutes_to_stroll_per_week + minutes_of_light_housework_per_week + minutes_of_heavy_housework_per_week 
  + other_active_minutes_per_week + hypertension + hyperlipidemia + high_cholesterol + diabetes + coronary_heart_disease + peptic_ulcer 
  + osteoarticular_diseases + cervical_spondylosis + occupational_disease + unknown + no_disease + frequency_of_exercise 
  + feelings_during_exercise + exercise_projects + exercise_reasons + exercise_disorders + chest_circumference + waist_circumference + hip_circumference + upper_arm_skin_fold_thickness 
  + scapular_skin_fold_thickness + abdomen_skin_fold_thickness + resting_heart_rate + systolic_blood_pressure + diastolic_blood_pressure 
  + (1|age_group.ord) + (1|region) + (1|educational_level.ord) + (1|whether_to_exercise_or_not) + (1|exercise_time.ord) 
)
mixedmodel <- lmer(
  data = mydata
  ,formula = mixed.reg.formula
  ,control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa"))

Check independence of residuals by Durbin-Waston’s test.

performance::check_autocorrelation(mixedmodel)
## OK: Residuals appear to be independent and not autocorrelated (p = 0.424).

Check heteroscedasticity of residuals.

performance::check_heteroscedasticity(mixedmodel)
## Warning: Heteroscedasticity (non-constant error variance) detected (p < .001).

Implement weighted LMM. Define weightes as weighted MLR.

wt <- 1 / lm(abs(summary(mixedmodel)$residuals) ~ predict(mixedmodel))$fitted.values^2
mixedmodel.wt <- lmer(
  data     = mydata
  ,formula = mixed.reg.formula
  ,weights = wt
  ,control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa")
)

The likelihood ratio test showed that the variable “region” was not statistically significant as a random effect, so region was removed from the random effects.

mixedmodel.wt.ep <- update(mixedmodel.wt
                              , . ~ . - (1 |region) + region )

Linear trend test for continuous variables in weighted LMM.

mydata <- mydata %>% mutate(
  other_working_minutes_per_week.ord = factor(cut(other_working_minutes_per_week,breaks = 4,labels=c(1,2,3,4)),ordered = T),
  chest_circumference.ord = factor(cut(chest_circumference,breaks = 4,labels=c(1,2,3,4)),ordered = T),
  waist_circumference.ord = factor(cut(waist_circumference,breaks = 4,labels=c(1,2,3,4)),ordered = T),
  abdomen_skin_fold_thickness.ord = factor(cut(abdomen_skin_fold_thickness,breaks = 4,labels=c(1,2,3,4)),ordered = T),
  resting_heart_rate.ord = factor(cut(resting_heart_rate,breaks = 4,labels=c(1,2,3,4)),ordered = T),
 )
